    "In order to better understand this difference, let us introduce the marginal distributionh(t, w) = ∫ R f (t, A, w)dA.The Fokker-Planck equation ( 13) for the distribution h(t, w) reads∂ t h(t, w) = Qp (h, f)(t, w) + Qℓ (h, f ℓ)(t, w),(25)whereQp (h, f)(t, w) = σ 2 p 2 ∂ 2 w (D 2 (w)h(t, w)) + λ p ∂ w (K[f](t, w)h Ā,p (t, w)), Qℓ (h, f ℓ)(t, w) = σ 2 ℓ 2 ∂ 2 w (D 2 (w)h(t, w)) + λ ℓ ∂ w (J [f ℓ](w)h Ā,ℓ (t, w)),and we have definedh Ā,• (t, w) = ∫ R ( Āω • + ε)f (t, A, w)dA.While the Fokker-Planck equation ( 25) displays a very similar structure to already existing models [4,13,34,37], we can see the additional influence of the activity level appearing in the distributions h Ā,• (t, w) and in the operator K[f](t, w).",
    "The evolution of the marginal distribution h(t, w) will be explored in more details in Section 4.",
    "Increasing the number of active agents via control strategiesIn this section, we introduce a suitable control strategy to increase the overall activity level of the population.",
    "In the political sphere, this control strategy could be interpreted as a way to prevent abstentionism [17,18,25].",
    "Our approach resembles the one introduced in [13] to avoid consensus formation on a graphon: we include an additional microscopic dynamic to prevent the formation of a large group of inactive agents."
